      "simpleDefinition": "Laws passed by Parliament that are mandatory and must be followed.",
      "anchor": "The Law of the Land.",
      "misconception": "Thinking these are just 'best practice' rather than legal requirements that can lead to prosecution."
    },
    {
      "term": "Non-statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Professional standards and guidance that describe how to work safely but are not laws themselves.",
      "anchor": "The Industry Rulebook.",
      "misconception": "Believing that because they aren't law, they can be ignored without any legal or professional consequence."
    },
    {
      "term": "HASAWA (Health and Safety at Work Act)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The primary statutory law that sets out the general duties of employers and employees for workplace safety.",
      "anchor": "The Umbrella Act.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it only applies to the 'boss' and not to the individual electrician on site."
    },
    {
      "term": "EAWR (Electricity at Work Regulations)",
      "simpleDefinition": "Statutory regulations specifically designed to prevent death or injury from electrical causes in the workplace.",
      "anchor": "The Electrician's Law.",
      "misconception": "Confusing these legal requirements with the technical rules found in BS 7671."
    },
    {
      "term": "BS 7671 (IET Wiring Regulations)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The main non-statutory national standard for the design and installation of electrical systems.",
      "anchor": "The Big Blue Book.",
      "misconception": "Thinking BS 7671 is a statutory law; it is actually non-statutory guidance used to prove you've met the law."
    },
    {
      "term": "On-Site Guide",
      "simpleDefinition": "A non-statutory handbook that provides simplified, practical instructions for common electrical installations.",
      "anchor": "The Pocket Reference.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the On-Site Guide covers every complex situation found in the full BS 7671 regulations."
    },
    {
      "term": "ACOP (Approved Codes of Practice)",
      "simpleDefinition": "Guidance that has a special legal status; if you don't follow it, you must prove your method was just as safe.",
      "anchor": "The 'Follow or Prove' Rules.",
      "misconception": "Assuming that 'Codes of Practice' are just optional suggestions with no weight in a courtroom."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Statutory means it is the law.",
    "Non-statutory is the professional standard.",
    "EAWR is the law; BS 7671 is the guidance.",
    "Failure to follow statutory regulations is a criminal offense."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "BS 7671 is not a law, but it is the standard used to comply with the law.",
    "Statutory regulations apply to everyone on site, not just the employer.",
    "Non-statutory guidance is often used in court to define 'safe working practice'."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "The Legal Hierarchy",
      "objective": "Explanation A",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the UK electrical industry, rules are divided into two main categories: Statutory and Non-statutory. Statutory regulations are the 'Law of the Land.' These are acts of Parliament that you must follow by law. If you break a statutory regulation, you are committing a criminal offense, which can lead to fines or even imprisonment.",
        "Non-statutory regulations are the 'Industry Rulebook.' These are professional standards and codes of practice that provide technical guidance on how to work safely. While they are not laws themselves, they are used in court to prove whether you have met your legal obligations. For example, if you follow the industry standard, you can demonstrate that you were working to a safe level. Understanding the difference is vital because while the law tells you that you must be safe, the guidance tells you exactly how to achieve that safety through technical specifications."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about which one is a law passed by Parliament and which one is a technical guide."
    },
    {
      "title": "How Laws and Guidance Work Together",
      "objective": "Explanation B",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Statutory and non-statutory documents work together to ensure safety on site. Statutory regulations are often written in broad, 'absolute' terms. For example, a law might state that 'all systems shall be maintained so as to prevent danger.' However, the law doesn't explain the specific wire size or fuse type you need to use to prevent that danger.",
        "This is where non-statutory guidance, such as BS 7671 (The IET Wiring Regulations), comes in. BS 7671 provides the specific technical rules for design and installation. By following the non-statutory rules in BS 7671, you are effectively meeting the legal requirements set out in statutory laws like the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR). You use the guidance as a practical tool to ensure you stay on the right side of the law. If an accident happens and you haven't followed the guidance, it becomes very difficult to prove in court that you were working safely."
      ],
      "hint": "Consider which document provides the specific technical details like cable sizes."
    },
    {
      "title": "Core Statutory Regulations",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: statutory regulations.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "As an electrician, you must be familiar with specific statutory regulations. The primary law is the Health and Safety at Work Act (HASAWA), which acts as an 'Umbrella Act' covering all workplace safety. Underneath this, we have the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR), which is the specific law for our trade. The EAWR 1989 sets out legal duties to prevent death or injury from electricity.",
        "Other key statutory laws include the Electricity Safety, Quality and Continuity Regulations (ESQCR), which mainly concern the supply of electricity to buildings. There is also the Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations, which requires risk assessments. Because these are statutory, they apply to everyone on a job site—including the employer, the employee, and the self-employed. You cannot 'opt out' of these; they are mandatory legal requirements that carry the threat of criminal prosecution if ignored."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the acronyms like HASAWA and EAWR which represent the 'Law of the Land'."
    },
    {
      "title": "Non-statutory Guidance and Standards",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: non-statutory regulations/guidance.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Non-statutory documents are the technical manuals we use daily. The most important is BS 7671, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations or 'The Big Blue Book.' This is the national standard for electrical installations in the UK. While BS 7671 is not a law passed by Parliament, it is the 'standard of care' expected by the industry and the courts.",
        "Other non-statutory sources include the On-Site Guide, which is a simplified pocket reference for common installation tasks, and various Guidance Notes that go into deep detail on specific topics like testing or emergency lighting. You might also use the Unite Union Book or specific Codes of Practice. These documents are updated frequently to keep up with new technology. Even though they aren't 'laws,' failing to follow them is considered professional negligence and can result in you losing your job, your registration with a professional body, or losing a civil court case."
      ],
      "hint": "Look for the documents that provide technical 'how-to' instructions, like BS 7671."
    },
    {
      "title": "Identifying Specific Statutory Acts",
      "objective": "Teach the core idea: 203.LO1.AC1.1.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To work safely on a modern construction site, you must identify several other statutory regulations beyond just electrical ones. PUWER (Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations) ensures that the tools you use, like drills or ladders, are safe and maintained. COSHH (Control of Substances Hazardous to Health) regulates how you handle dangerous chemicals, such as cleaning solvents or resins.",
        "Other essential statutory acts include the CDM (Construction Design and Management) regulations, which manage site safety and coordination, and the PPE (Personal Protective Equipment) at Work Regulations, which mandate the use of safety gear like boots and hard hats. You must also be aware of the Manual Handling Operations Regulations for lifting heavy loads and the Noise at Work Regulations. Every one of these is a statutory requirement, meaning they are legally binding and enforceable by the Health and Safety Executive (HSE)."
      ],
      "hint": "Identify the acronyms that relate to specific site safety laws like tools (PUWER) or chemicals (COSHH)."
    }
  ]
}

